The first time I stepped foot into Ganni's was December 15th, 2016, at 1am. It was 22 degrees out, and the windows were fogged as I crossed the street. As I entered through the grimy glass door, security gate overhead, I was met with a wall of noise - a table of off duty patrol cops sharing a joke. A tall yuppie in a beautiful camel peacoat was yelling at the owner, Ganni himself. A short, balding Italian man, Ganni will call you "my friend", "buddy", or "man", regardless of your race, gender, or your actual demeanor towards him. Standing in that doorway, the color and sound rocked me back, a vivid still life of America. Remembering back to that moment brings with it every smell and sound and sight. Like the immutable drive of a salmon to return to the river it was born in, that restaurant calls me back, again and again. New York is not a place I could live. It's too brash and the current of life moves too swiftly, but Ganni's rises just above that. It is a place of rest for the drunk and hungry, a place where time slows down a little bit. Just you, Ganni, and a slice of pizza.

5 stars for a slices place. This place is a typical fast slices place. While reasonably clean, keep in mind it is far from a deluxe atmosphere. There are 4 tables and some other seats, so you can typically sit and enjoy your slices.  The pizza here is very very good. The veggie pizza is positively LOADED with good quality veggies. The pepperoni bacon pizza has the prefect amount of meat and plenty of cheese. Two slices made me very full.  Their specialty seems to be chicken/bacon/ranch pizza. Diced chicken, bacon pieces, drizzled in ranch dressing. It was amazingly tasty.  If you want to get some delicious pizza, this a great place. If you are looking for a table cloth and a bottle of wine, this is the opposite of what you are looking for.
